Abstract

Cloud computing is a computing model, where resources such as computing power, storage, network and software are abstracted and provided as services on the Internet in a remotely accessible fashion. Billing models for these services are generally similar to the ones adopted for public utilities. On-demand availability, ease of provisioning, dynamic and virtually infinite scalability are some of the key attributes of cloud computing.

An infrastructure setup based on the cloud computing model is generally referred to as the "cloud". The following are the broad categories of services available on the cloud:

• Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)

• Platform as a Service (PaaS)

• Software as a Service (SaaS)

Amazon Web Services (AWS) is one of the major players providing IAAS. They have two popular services - Elastic Compute Cloud (EC2) and Simple Storage Service (S3). These services are available through web services.

OpenStack is a stack of open source software that enterprises/service providers can use to setup and run their cloud compute and storage infrastructure. RackSpace and NASA are the key initial contributors to the stack. Rackspace contributed their "Cloud Files" platform to power the Object Storage part of the OpenStack, while NASA contributed their "Nebula" code to power the Compute part. OpenStack consortium has managed to have more than 50 members including IBM, Canonical, Dell, Citrix etc.

We would be building a Minimal Cloud Infrastructure powered by Ubuntu and Open Stack in order to demonstrate the feasibility and power of Cloud Computing to deal with the twin challenges of driving the high costs of information technology down while providing innovative new solutions to improve the business.


Introduction

Cloud computing has two distinctly different meanings. The first is simple: The use of any commercial service delivered over the Internet in real time, from Amazon's EC2 to software as a service offered by the likes of Salesforce or Google.

The second meaning of cloud computing describes the architecture and technologies necessary to provide cloud services. The idea is that you get all the scalability, metering, and time-to-market benefits of a public cloud service without ceding control, security, and recurring costs to a service provider. This is called as Private Cloud. The technologies underlying it are pretty obvious, beginning with virtualization (for easy scalability, flexible resource management, and maximum hardware utilization) and data center automation (mainly for auto-provisioning of physical hosts). Chargeback metering keeps business management happy (look, we can see the real cost of IT!), and identity-based security helps ensure only authorized people get access to the infrastructure and application resources they need.

On one hand, the private cloud is just another step toward the commodification of IT, where internal customers pick from a menu of metered services across a virtualized infrastructure, rather than specifying the nth requirement for custom deployments that tie up resources forever. On the other hand, one of the most exciting use cases for the private cloud is the ability for enterprises to establish quasi-public clouds for partners, which may accelerate business-to-business e-commerce in unanticipated ways.


Motivation of Cloud Computing

Although the Computing power of machines increase rapidly with time, never failing the infamous Moore's Law, however so do the computing needs increase at an amazing rate.

However even with increasing power, Traditional model of IT Infrastructure suffer from higher maintainence, lack of flexibility, require more power, floor space, and require much of the financial and manpower resources of an organisation.

Cloud solutions can form the basis of a next generation data center strategy, bringing agility, elasticity, and economic viability to the fore.


  1. Reduced capital expenditures - Upfront costs are dramatically reduced since the onus of initial computing infrastructure investments rests primarily on the cloud computing provider. Ongoing costs are also lower due to economies of scale and multi-tenancy, which allows access to the lower cost of cloud computing resources even for very infrequent tasks.

  2. Low barrier to entry - Because hardware and software does not have to be acquired, installed, provisioned for every need and resources can be tapped on-demand, often in real-time, cloud computing can be as easy as moving existing applications into a hosted data center, although this depends entirely on the architectural model of the cloud computing provider.

  3. Multitenancy - Multiple customers share many of the same resources in the cloud computing model. This sharing both distributes cost and enables economies of scale in terms of centralization of resources including real estate, bandwidth, and power. Multitenancy is one of the key enablers of efficiency while at the same time posing certain security issues.

  4. Security - In theory, cloud computing can be more secure than do-it-yourself computing since shared costs allow larger overall investment in security processes and infrastructure. However, there remain worries about access and control over an organization’s sensitive data, though to-date the security record of cloud computing has been quite good.

  5. Scalability and performance - Cloud computing can provide access to very high levels of scale without enormous costs of traditional infrastructure. Resources don’t have to kept on hand for peaks that then remain dormant much of the time and their costs stranded during valleys. Performance of cloud computing can also be very good since many providers have data centers around the world to keep the processing reasonably close to those accessing it over the network. However the distances between the business and the services in the cloud are usually greater than from a local data center. The resulting latency can frequently be a bit larger than with local resources though often quite acceptable for many applications.

  6. Service-oriented - Cloud computing is a service delivered over the network, but true service-orientation allows such services to be componentized, pluggable, composable, and loosely coupled. OpenID is a good example of such a service that has a well-defined interface and for which there are many providers in the cloud which are essentially interchangeable. Cloud computing has become increasingly service-oriented, with Amazon probably being the farthest along in maturity and breadth of services. In the end, cloud computing is making the Web truly become a Global SOA.

Types of Cloud

Cloud Computing can be classified into 4 types on the basis of location where the cloud is hosted:

  • Public Cloud: Computing infrastructure is hosted at the vendor’s premises. The customer has no visibility over the location of the cloud computing infrastructure. The computing infrastructure is shared between organizations.

  • Private Cloud: Computing architecture is dedicated to the customer and is not shared with other organisations. They are expensive and are considered more secure than Public Clouds. Private clouds may be externally hosted ones as well as in premise hosted clouds.

  • Hybrid Cloud: Organisations host some critical, secure applications in private clouds. The not so critical applications are hosted in the public cloud. The combination is known as Hybrid Cloud. Cloud bursting is the term used to define a system where the organisation uses its own infrastructure for normal usage, but cloud is used for peak loads.

  • Community Cloud: The cloud infrastructure is shared between the organizations of the same community. For example, all the government agencies in a city can share the same cloud but not the non government agencies.


In this project we shall deal with creating our own Private cloud using OpenStack with Ubuntu as the base OS.



Materials and Methods

Hardware Requirements

Setting up Hardware

OpenStack components are intended to run on standard hardware. The processor should support Hardware Virtualization, either AMD-V or Intel VT-x will do. Preferably a system with Athlon64 or new processor with 1GB RAM and 20GB hard disk space.

Networking Requirements

100 Mbps are suggested for the LAN. For OpenStack Compute, networking is configured on multi-node installations between the physical machines on a single subnet.



Software Requirements

Operating System

OpenStack will run on Ubuntu and the deployment-level considerations will be Ubuntu-centric.

Database

For OpenStack Compute, access to either a PostgreSQL or MySQL database is needed, or it can be installed it as part of the OpenStack Compute installation process.

Permissions

OpenStack needs root permission for installation and configuration. It can also be achieved with sudo access via the suoders configuration.


Ubuntu Server

In this project Ubuntu 11.04 Server Edition, will be used as the host operating system, which will run the cloud computing infrastructure.

Using Debian as a foundation, the Ubuntu Server Edition, also called Ubuntu server, offers support for several common configurations, and also simplifies common Linux server deployment processes. Standard Internet services such as e-mail, Web, DNS, file serving and database management can be integrated. Ubuntu offers supports for OpenStack and bundles OpenStack as the default Cloud Infrastructure in Ubuntu Enterprise Cloud (UEC) since release 11.04 when it replaced Eucalyptus.


OpenStack

The OpenStack Project aims to create an open source cloud computing platform for public and private clouds aimed at scalability without complexity. Initially focusing on Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) offerings, the project currently encompasses three components:

  • OpenStack Compute: Software to orchestrate, manage, and offer virtual machines. The software for this is called “Nova.”

  • OpenStack Object Store: Software for the redundant storage of static objects. The

  • software for this is called “Swift.”

  • OpenStack Image Service: Provides query and storage services for virtual disk images. The software for this is called “Glance.”



One of the defining core values behind the project is its embrace of openness with both open standards and open source code. OpenStack has been released under the Apache 2.0 license. If you are unfamiliar with the license, you should review the full license or skip to the layman’s terms. In addition, OpenStack promotes open standards through the OpenStack API.


The OpenStack project began through the work of two organizations: Rackspace Hosting (a large US hosting firm) and NASA (the US Space agency) decided to join forces and release their internal cloud object storage and cloud compute code bases (respectively) as a common open source project.


Open Stack Compute Infrastructure (Nova)

Nova is the underlying cloud computing fabric controller for the OpenStack cloud. All activities needed to support the life cycle of instances within the OpenStack cloud are handled by Nova. It manages all the compute resources, networking, authorization, and scalability needs of the OpenStack cloud. Nova is a management platform and does not provide any virtualization capabilities by itself; instead, it uses libvirt APIs to interact with the supported hypervisors. Nova exposes its capabilities through a web services API that is compatible with that of EC2 of Amazon Web Services.

Functions and Features:

  • Instance life cycle management

  • Management of compute resources

  • Networking and Authorization

  • REST-based API

  • Asynchronous eventually consistent communication

  • Hypervisor agnostic: support for Xen, KVM, QEMU and Hyper-V


Components of Nova

Nova Cloud Fabric is composed of the following major components:

  • API Server ( nova-api )

  • Message Queue ( rabbit-mq server )

  • Compute Workers ( nova-compute )

  • Network Controller ( nova-network )

  • Volume Worker ( nova-volume )

  • Scheduler ( nova-scheduler )


API Server ( nova-api )

API Server provides an interface to the outside world to interact with the cloud infrastructure. API server is the only component that outside world uses to manage the infrastructure. The management is done through web services calls using EC2 API. API Server in turns communicates with the relevant components of the cloud infrastructure through the Message Queue.


Message Queue ( Rabbit MQ Server )

OpenStack Cloud Controller communicates with other nova components such as Scheduler, Network Controller, and Volume Controller. Nova uses asynchronous calls for request response, with a call-back that gets triggered once a response is received. Since asynchronous communication is used, none of the end points get stuck for long in a waiting state.


Compute Worker ( nova-compute )

Compute workers deal with instance management life cycle. They receive the requests for life cycle management via the Message Queue and carry out operations. There are several Compute Workers in a typical production cloud deployment. An instance is deployed on any of the available compute worker based on the scheduling algorithm used.


Network Controller ( nova-network )

The Network Controller deals with the network configuration of host machines. It does operations like allocating IP addresses, configuring VLANs for projects, implementing security groups and configuring networks for compute nodes.


Volume Workers ( nova-volume )

Volume workers are used for the management of LVM-based instance volumes. Volume Workers perform volume related functions such as creation, deletion, attaching a volume to an instance, and detaching a volume from an instance. Volumes provide a way of providing persistent storage for use by instances, as the main disk attached to an instance is non-persistent and any changes made to it are lost when the volume is detached or the instance is terminated. When a volume is detached from an instance or when an instance, to which the volume is attached, is terminated, it retains the data that was stored on it when it was attached to an instance earlier. This data can be accessed by reattaching the volume to the same instance or by attaching it to another instance.

Any valuable data that gets accumulated during the life cycle of an instance should be written to a volume, so that it can be accessed later. This typically applies to the storage needs of database servers, etc.


Scheduler (nova-scheduler)

The scheduler maps the nova-API calls to the appropriate openstack components. It runs as a daemon named nova-schedule and picks up a compute/network/volume server from a pool of available resources depending upon the scheduling algorithm in place. A scheduler can base its decisions on various factors such as load, memory, physical distance of the availability zone, CPU architecture, etc. The nova scheduler implements a pluggable architecture.


OpenStack Storage Infrastructure (Swift)

Swift is an object store to store a large number of objects distributed across commodity hardware. Swift has built-in redundancy and failover management and features like backing up or archiving data, serving graphics or videos. It is scalable to multiple petabytes and to billions of objects. Swift provides elasticity and flexibility of cloud based storage for your web applications.


Functions and Features

  • Storing the machine images

  • Working as an independent data container

  • Redundancy and Failover

  • Backup and Archival

  • Extremely scalable


OpenStack Imaging Service (Glance)

OpenStack Imaging Service is a lookup and retrieval system for virtual machine images. It can be configured to use any one of the following 3 storage backends:

  • OpenStack Object Store to store images

  • S3 storage directly

  • S3 storage with Object Store as the intermediate for S3 access.


Functions and Featues ( Glance )

• Provides imaging service


Components of OpenStack Imaging Service ( Glance )

• Glance-api

• Glance-registry


Design

This project focuses on setting up a Cloud Computing Infrastructure using OpenStack on Ubuntu 11.04 and we'll be covering installing Nova, or OpenStack Compute on a single server. At the end of this project we would have a stable OpenStack Compute machine on your network that you can create users on and start and stop VM guests.

With the deployment in action, a Business user or developer will be able to have easy provisioning of VM images and instance management as OpenStack will be able to abstract the lower level details of virtualization, hardware, disk space and network. Our main focus will be a look as an IT administrator as an IT manager will be able to create templates and instances and be able to perform various kinds of administration tasks.

In this deployment, we’ll basically focus on Nova and Glance. Nova is the underlying cloud computing fabric controller for the OpenStack cloud. All activities needed to support the life cycle of instances within the OpenStack cloud are handled by Nova. It manages all the compute resources, networking, authorization, and scalability needs of the OpenStack cloud. Nova is a management platform and does not provide any virtualization capabilities by itself; instead, it uses libvirt APIs to interact with the supported hypervisors. For the purpose of the project we will be using KVM - Kernel-based Virtual Machine (KVM) is a virtualization infrastructure for the Linux kernel. It’s a Virtual Machine Implementation that uses the Linux Kernel. Invented and maintained by Qumranet, a technology startup acquired by Red Hat in 2008, KVM is included out-of-the-box with Linux versions 2.6.20 and above. We’ll also focus on Glance, the OpenStack Imaging Service is a lookup and retrieval system for virtual machine images. Focus will not be much of Swift which is an object store to store a large number of objects distributed across commodity hardware as we will manage all operations using nova-manage and euca2ools.

The above picture simplified version of OpenStack with which we are basically dealing with in this project. Together these form the framework for our OpenStack cloud infrastructure running on Ubuntu.


Working

Installation and Configuration of the Host

Setting up Hardware

Basically we need a modern machine, with enough CPU horsepower and memory to handle the virtual instances. Preferably we’ll need a processor which supports Hardware Virtualization like Intel VT or AMD-V technologies.

The processor should have enough horsepower to handle the multiplicity of the instances, and for this reason multi-core and multi-processor system will be preferred. And since each instance will require dedicated memory, the host computer should have enough gigabytes of memory to accommodate all their needs, along with the needs of the host, for this reason at least 1GB of RAM is bare minimum. Also, a CD-ROM or DVD-ROM drive is essential in order to install the host operating system. Network Card is an important need for this configuration. Reliability is a very vital need as well, the hardware should be rock-solid and preferably have power backup in case of a power surge. We would also require a secondary PC preferably to remotely access and manage the cloud infrastructure.


Test System

As covered, our test system has the following specs:

  • CPU: AMD Athlon64 X2 4400+ @ 2.3 GHz

  • GPU: NVIDIA GeForce 8800GT

  • 2 GB RAM

  • 250 GB Hard disk space


Plan for the Host Operating System

For the host platform, Ubuntu 11.04 is the operating system of choice. It has to be installed into the subject machine. There are many techniques of installing, such as through Physical Media such as Optical Media like CD-ROM or DVD-ROM, or Hard Disk, USB Device, or through the network via FTP, HTTP, and NFS. For this project, installation of Ubuntu 11.04 through any technique will suffice; here Optical media will be used.

During the installation, we have to make sure to install the right software and do not install packages which will conflict with our cloud deployment.

If the network is configured with DHCP, we can simply set our Network Interface to use DHCP to automatically assign the IP address. In case the network is not configured with DHCP or DHCP is not desired, we have to mnaually set the Static IP, Netmaks, and the gateway; and also the DNS.

The root partition should be of enough size to accommodate all the programs, and even the user directories and virtual machine images if no separate partitions are created. In addition we have to create an additional volume to use for nova-volumes (covered later). These volumes would be attached to the guest instances.


Installing Packages

The Ubuntu 11.04 Server


its default desktop looks like the above. It’s a complete operating system which offers various range of software, and with our installation for our host, we have our Virtualization system installed as well.

Ideally at this point after installation, we should apply updates, and set up additional repositories if it’s required.

We can update with the command:

sudo apt-get update && sudo apt-get upgrade


Setting up and configuring OpenStack

After getting our distribution up to date and synced, we need to install the prerequisites.

Configuring the system for Virtualization with KVM

Since our cloud infrastructure uses libvirt, and our choice of virtualization technology is KVM, we use the KVM hypervisor.

We know that KVM, Kernel-based Virtual Machine, is a hypervisor built right into the 2.6 (and 3.X) Linux kernel for kernels newer than 2.6.20. To start using the hypervisor, we just load the appropriate kvm kernel modules and the hypervisor is up. Now in order for KVM to work, we must have a processor that supports Intel's VT-x extensions or AMD's AMD-V extensions. Of course the appropriate packages should be installed in our host system.

In order to really confirm that the kernel supports KVM, we can issue the following command to check.

su –c 'modprobe -l 'kvm*'

We have to check if your computer supports KVM hardware acceleration with the following command. It must return something.

egrep '^flags.*(vmx|svm)' /proc/cpuinfo

Firstly, we need to add our user into the kvm group to use the /dev/kvm device.

gpasswd -a <Your_Login_Name> kvm

We have to replace the <Your_Login_Name> by the login name we are supposed to execute kvm with. Like in this project:

gpasswd –a user1 kvm

Secondly, we have to choose one of the following depending on the manufacturer of our CPU.

If we have Intel's VT-x extensions, modprobe the kvm and kvm-intel modules.

modprobe kvm

modprobe kvm-intel

If we have AMD's AMD-V extensions, modprobe the kvm and kvm-amd modules.

modprobe kvm

modprobe kvm-amd

If modprobing kvm succeeds, but modprobing kvm-intel or kvm-amd fails (but /proc/cpuinfo claims that hardware acceleration is supported), we have to check our BIOS settings. Some vendors (especially laptop vendors) disable these processor extensions by default.

After we perform these steps our system should be ready to be virtualizing with KVM.

And thus we can prepare our guest OS installation media.


Install prerequisites

Now that we are sure that virtualization works on our single machine, let’s complete a few more dependencies for Nova. Install RabbitMQ as our message queue by adding the rabbitmq-server package.

sudo apt-get install rabbitmq-server

This will drag along a number of packages. We can check whether it is working with rabiitmqctl.

sudo rabbitmqctl status

Install MySQL as our database with the mysql-server package if it is not already not installed.

sudo apt-get install mysql-server

When it asks for the root’s MySQL password, we have to remember to write it down as it will be used later.

Then we create databases for Nova and Glance. We use the MySQL server over SQLite and PostegreSQL in this project.

mysql –u root –p<password>

In the MySQL console, we create a database for Nova and set a username to access it, and set a password for it.

mysql> CREATE DATABASE nova;

mysql> GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON nova.* to 'nova'@'%' WITH GRANT OPTION;

mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR 'nova'@'%' = PASSWORD('nova');

Similarly we create and authorize a database for glance.

mysql> CREATE DATABASE glance;

mysql> GRANT ALL PRIVILEGES ON glance.* to 'glance'@'%' WITH GRANT OPTION;

mysql> SET PASSWORD FOR 'glance'@'%' = PASSWORD('glance');

Finally we add a few final prerequisite packages for this specific configuration.

sudo apt-get install python-greenlet python-mysqldb

sudo apt-get install python-software-properties

The final prerequisite is installing and configuring iSCSI for nova-volume, iSCSI is an Internet Protocol (IP)-based storage networking standard which will be used by nova-volume.

We first need to build the linux headers package for our specified kernel.

sudo apt-get install linux-headers-`uname –r`

The `uname –r` command will replace the version of the kernel so that to package manager will be able to install the correct kernel headers package.

sudo apt-get iscsitarget

To start iSCSI services, we have to simply make sure that ISCITARGET_ENABLE option is set to true in the /etc/default/iscsitarget file, and start the iscsitarget service.

sudo sed –i 's/false/true/g' /etc/default/iscsitarget

sudo service iscsitarget start

We also need to create a Volume Group with Linux Volume Manage (LVM). To create a volume group on an existing partition say, /dev/sdc1, we issue the following commands.

sudo pvcreate /dev/sdc1

sudo vgcreate nova-volumes /dev/sdc1

Install glance

We move on to installing the glance packages. Glance is our image service.

sudo apt-get install glance python-glance-doc

We now need to modify Glance to use the MySQL server instead of the default SQLite. So we edit /etc/glance/glance.conf and change the corresponding line to:

--sql_connection=mysql://glance:glance@127.0.0.1/glance

These are the username, password, and the database for MySQL respectively.

Once installed, it needs to be started with the glance-control utility.

sudo glance-control all start

And we can check the status of images with the command.

glance index

At this point of time the command will output: No public images found.


Install nova

We now move on to install the Nova packages, which will drag a few more dependencies with it. We type the following commands:

sudo apt-get install nova-common nova-doc nova-api nova-network

sudo apt-get install nova-objectore nova-scheduler nova-compute

sudo apt-get install nova-common nova-volume python-nova unzip

These commands will install the nova packages, all with their dependencies. At this point of time, we run the following command to make sure all our services are running.

sudo nova-manage service list

This should show the output:

cactus nova-network enabled :-) 2012-02-10 00:04:39.928905

cactus nova-compute enabled :-) 2012-02-10 00:04:40.154642

cactus nova-scheduler enabled :-) 2012-02-10 00:04:40.044152

cactus nova-volume enabled :-) 2012-02-10 00:04:43.540773

If we see all the smiley faces, this means Nova is installed correctly. Otherwise we need to look at the logs located at /var/log/nova and identify the problems and fix them accordingly.


Configuring OpenStack

First let us configure it to use our MySQL database that we had created earlier. To do this, we just add the following flag to /etc/nova/nova.conf config file.

We configure Nova to use the MySQL database and mention the driver – MySQL, credentials and the database.

--sql_connection=mysql://nova:nova@127.0.0.1/nova

We also set our configuration to use KVM for virtualization, we do have to make sure that our CPU supports hardware acceleration.

--libvirt_type=kvm

Now we set Nova to use our glance installation by adding two options to /etc/nova/nova.conf:

--glance_host=127.0.0.1

--image_service=nova.image.glance.GlanceImageService

With that completed, we’ll move to the configuration of the networking options. First up is adding the network manager, setting the local cloud IPs and size.

--network_manager=nova.network.manager.FlatDHCPManager

--fixed_range=10.0.0.8

--network_size=8

It has to be noted that this fixed IP range will be the IPs allocated to the hosts as well as the cloud instances and will be local to the cloud deployment. It is important that these IP do NOT clash with other LAN IPs.

Now that our basic configuration is completed, we can create the database schema by running the nova-manage db commands. First of all, we will sync the database i.e. create the schema, and then we will version the database to make sure that the schema creation succeeded.

sudo nova-manage db sync

sudo nova-manage db version

And now we would need to set the network for the OpenStack cloud configuration. Both the local IPs as well as the floating IPs.

First we add out network into the database with the nova-manage command.

sudo nova-manage network create 10.0.0.0/8 1 8

Finally, we will will create the floating addresses using a range which will not overlap with the addresses in the local network.

sudo nova-manage floating create ubuntu 192.168.1.136/29

The range is defined with CIDR notation. The name “ubuntu” should match the hostname. As our hostname was defined as “ubuntu” during installation, so we are using it here.


We install euca2ools in order to have tools to manage our images and instances using the Amazon EC2 API.

sudo apt-get install euca2ools

And now we are done with the configuration, we restart our machine, or just all the nova and glance services to take our configuration to take effect.



Image Deployment and Management

Now that we have a working Nova installation, we need to ready it for use by our initial users. This requires us to do some command line configuration on the Nova Controller. First, we will add a user, and create credentials to user to control the Nova Controller. Then we will build a virtual disk image, and upload that virtual image disk to glance and the launch the instance and finally configure the network access for it.

Creating User and Projects

The first step in using our new Nova installation is to create a user. This is a multi-step process that uses the nova-manage utility to create a project.

nova-manage user create techfundo

nova-manage role add techfundo cloudadmin

nova-manage project create book techfundo

nova-manage project zipfile book techfundo

The final command will produce a zip-compressed file called nova.zip. We uncompress the credential zip file and source the resulting novarc. This will set the environmental variables needed to access our Nova installation with other utilities. Any user with access to the zipfile will assume the role of the cloud user admin.

unzip nova.zip

source novarc

We can add these commands to our .bashrc so that the credentials are identified in every session.

Now it is time to create a virtual machine image which could be uploaded into glance to create our instances. For the project we will use the Ubuntu 11.04 Server (same as host) as the instance OS.


Creating a Linux Image – Ubuntu

The first step would be to create a raw image on Client1. This will represent the main HDD of the virtual machine, so we have to make sure to give it as much space as you will need.

kvm-img create -f raw server.img 5G

OS Installation

We download the ISO file of the Ubuntu 11.04 Server (Natty Narwhal) 64-bit.

wget <link to download ISO>

We boot a KVM instance with the OS installer ISO in the virtual CD-ROM. This will start the installation process. The command below also sets up a VNC display at port 0.

sudo kvm -m 256 -cdrom ubuntu-11.04-server-amd64.iso -drive file=server.img,if=scsi,index=0 -boot d -net nic -net user -nographic ~-vnc :0


We connect to the VM through VNC (use display number :0) and finish the installation.

For Example, if 10.10.10.4 is the IP address:

vncviewer 10.10.10.4 :0

During the installation of Ubuntu, create a single ext4 partition mounted on ‘/’. We do not create a swap partition.

After finishing the installation, relaunch the VM by executing the following command.

sudo kvm -m 256 -drive file=server.img,if=scsi,index=0,boot=on -boot c -net nic -net user - ←

nographic -vnc :0


At this point, we can add all the packages we want to have installed, update the installation, add users and make any configuration changes we want in our image.

At the minimum, for Ubuntu we may run the following commands

sudo apt-get update

sudo apt-get upgrade

sudo apt-get install openssh-server cloud-init

We also remove the network persistence rules from /etc/udev/rules.d as their presence will cause problems in cloud deployment.

sudo rm -rf /etc/udev/rules.d/70-persistent-net.rules

We shutdown the virtual machine and proceed with the next steps.


Extracting the EXT4 partition

The image that needs to be uploaded to OpenStack needs to be an ext4 filesystem image. Here are the steps to create a ext4 filesystem image from the raw image i.e server.img.

sudo losetup -f

server.img

sudo losetup -a

We should see an output like this:

/dev/loop0: [0801]:16908388 ($filepath)

We observe the name of the loop device (/dev/loop0 in our setup) when $filepath is the path to the mounted .raw file. Now we need to find out the starting sector of the partition. Run:

sudo fdisk -cul /dev/loop0

We should see an output like this:

Disk /dev/loop0: 5368 MB, 5368709120 bytes

149 heads, 8 sectors/track, 8796 cylinders, total 10485760 sectors

Units = sectors of 1 * 512 = 512 bytes

Sector size (logical/physical): 512 bytes / 512 bytes

I/O size (minimum/optimal): 512 bytes / 512 bytes

Disk identifier: 0x00072bd4

Device Boot Start End Blocks /dev/loop0p1 *2048 10483711 5240832 83 Linux Id System


We make a note of the starting sector of the /dev/loop0p1 partition i.e the partition whose ID is 83. This number should be multiplied by 512 to obtain the correct value of the offset in bytes. In this case: 2048 x 512 = 1048576.

We unmount the loop0 device:

sudo losetup -d /dev/loop0

Now we mount only the partition(/dev/loop0p1) of server.img which we had previously noted down, by adding the -o parameter with value previously calculated value.

sudo losetup -f -o 1048576 server.img

sudo losetup -a

We’ll see a message like this:

/dev/loop0: [0801]:16908388 ($filepath) offset 1048576

We make a note of the mount point of our device(/dev/loop0 in our setup) when $filepath is the path to the mounted .raw file. And we copy the entire partition to a new .raw file

sudo dd if=/dev/loop0 of=serverfinal.img

Now we have our ext4 filesystem image i.e serverfinal.img

Unmount the loop0 device

sudo losetup -d /dev/loop0


Tweaking /etc/fstab

We will need to tweak /etc/fstab to make it suitable for a cloud instance. nova-compute may resize the disk at the time of launch of instances based on the instance type chosen. This can make the UUID of the disk invalid. Hence we have to use file system label as the identifier for the partition instead of the UUID.

We loop-mount the serverfinal.img, by running:

sudo mount -o loop serverfinal.img /mnt

And making changes by editing /mnt/etc/fstab.

UUID=e7f5af8d-5d96-45cc-a0fc-d0d1bde8f31c / ext4 errors=remount-ro 0 1

to

LABEL=uec-rootfs / ext4 errors=remount-ro 0 1

Kernel and Initrd for OpenStack

We copy the kernel and the initrd image from /mnt/boot to user home directory. These will be used later for creating and uploading a complete virtual image to OpenStack.

sudo cp /mnt/boot/vmlinuz-2.6.38-7-server /home/localadmin

sudo cp /mnt/boot/initrd.img-2.6.38-7-server /home/localadmin

We unmount the Loop partition as it’s no longer needed.

sudo umount /mnt

We change the filesystem label of serverfinal.img to ’uec-rootfs’

sudo tune2fs -L uec-rootfs serverfinal.img

Now, we have all the components of the image ready to be uploaded to OpenStack imaging server.


Uploading Images

Before we can launch instances, we need to upload a Virtual Disk Image into Nova. This image has already been created in the previous step.

This step would be to upload the images to OpenStack Imaging Server glance. The files that need to be uploaded for the above sample setup of Ubuntu are: vmlinuz-2.6.38-7-server, initrd.img-2.6.38-7-server, serverfinal.img.

We run the following command

uec-publish-image -t image --kernel-file vmlinuz-2.6.38-7-server --ramdisk-file initrd.img -2.6.38-7-server amd64 serverfinal.img images


Here “images” is the container name.

Now we can see which images have been bundled with euca-describe-images command.

IMAGE aki-00000001 images/natty-server-uec-amd64-vmlinuz-virtual.manifest.xml available public x86_64 kernel


IMAGE ami-00000002 images/natty-server-uec-amd64.img.manifest.xml available public x86_64 machine aki-7eea4179


The emi=“ami-00000002” is the machine image. This machine image will be used to launch an instance. Similarly we can list our images with the command – nova image-list.

+------------+------+--------+

| ID | Name | Status |

+------------+------+--------+

| 1719908888 | None | ACTIVE |

| 2129281401 | None | ACTIVE |

+------------+------+--------+



Instance Management, Storage Management and Security

Now that we have a valid user and virtual disk image, we are ready to launch our first Nova instance. But before that, we need to make a keypair.

Creating Keypair

We need to create a keypair so that we will be able to log in to the new instance via SSH. To create our keypair, we use the euca-add-keypair tool.

euca-add-keypair techfundo > techfundo.pem

chmod 600 techfundo.pem

Now we have a key, we can launch an instance.

Launching Instances

Launching an instance via the EC2 API requires three arguments: the keypair name – “techfundo”, the size “m1.tiny” and the machine image “ami-00000002” that we uploaded to glance.

euca-run-instance –k techfundo –t m1.tiny ami-00000002

The instance starts scheduling, networking, and finally gets to run. We can check the status by euca-describe-instances.

RESERVATION r-1pkchwbm book default

INSTANCE i-00000001 ami-00000002 10.0.0.2 10.0.0.2 running

techfundo (book, nova-controller) 0 m1.tiny 2012-03-14T20:28:51Z nova

Similarly we can use nova-list to check the instances.

+----+----------+--------+---------------+------------+

| ID | Name | Status | Public IP | Private IP |

+----+----------+--------+---------------+------------+

| 1 | Server 1 | ACTIVE | | 10.0.0.2 |

+----+----------+--------+---------------+------------+



Configuring Network

With the instance up and running, we now need to configure the network access to it. This is a two step process: first we need to permit traffic to an instance. Then we need to associate a Floating IP to it. This floating IP is a public IP either a LAN IP or even a WAN IP, only assumption is that the network should route packets to the subnet. By configuring the floating IP, we will be able to access the instance outside nova like the Local Network or the entire World Wide Web.

Here we shall enable SSH, FTP, HTTP, and ICMP TCP packets and ICMP traffic from any IP address.

euca-authorize-default –P tcp –p 22 –s 0.0.0.0/0 # Enables SSH

euca-authorize-default –P tcp –p 21 –s 0.0.0.0/0 # Enables FTP

euca-authorize-default –P tcp –p 80 –s 0.0.0.0/0 # Enables HTTP

euca-authorize default –P icmp –t -1:-1 # Enables ICMP traffic

With traffic permitted to the instance, we now need to assign a public address to it. This is a two step process: first we allocate an address, then we associate it to an instance.

euca-allocate-address

Say we got an IP: 192.168.1.128

We associate it to our running instance.

euca-associate-address –i i-00000001 192.168.1.128

Now we can see a public IP has been assigned to our instance with nova list.

+----+----------+--------+---------------+------------+

| ID | Name | Status | Public IP | Private IP |

+----+----------+--------+---------------+------------+

| 1 | Server 1 | ACTIVE | 192.168.1.128 | 10.0.0.2 |

+----+----------+--------+---------------+------------+

We can now test our connectivity by pinging to the instance.

ping 192.168.1.128


Accessing Instances

With the network access completely configured, we are finally able to log in to our instance. Our image had been set up with SSH access with our keypair. So we can use SSH with our keypair filename (techfundo.pem).

Thus we log in to our instance by:

ssh –i techfundo.pem ubuntu@192.168.1.128

We can see our instance as:

Welcome to Ubuntu 11.04 (GNU/Linux 2.6.38-8-virtual x86_64)

* Documentation: https://help.ubuntu.com/

System information as of Tue March 27 11:12:18 UTC 2011

System load: 0.0 Processes: 61

Usage of /: 41.5% of 1.35GB Users logged in: 0

Memory usage: 19% IP address for eth0: 10.0.0.2

Swap usage: 0%


Graph this data and manage this system at https://landscape.canonical.com/

At the moment, only the core of the system is installed. To tune the

system to your needs, you can choose to install one or more

predefined collections of software by running the following

command:

sudo tasksel --section server

Last login: Mon Jul 4 23:50:50 2011 from 192.168.1.128

ubuntu@i-00000001:~$


So, we have finally installed our cloud, configured it ready for deployment and launched our first virtual machine. We can use our virtual machine as any other actual machine.


Attaching Volumes

We can create a volume by euca-create-volume with arguments with size –s 1 and –z nova for zone.

euca-create-volume –s 1 –s nova

Once the volume has been created, we can it to a running instance with the nova-attach-volume.

nova-attach-volume vol-00000001 –i i-00000001 –d /dev/vdb

Thus the volume will be attached to the instance “i-00000001” and show up as /dev/vdb. As with any raw device we would need to create a filesystem with it and mount it.

Create a mount point.

sudo mkdir /volumes

Format the volume as an Ext3 file system.

sudo mkfs –t ext3 /dev/vdb

Mount the volume at /volumes:

sudo mount /dev/vdb /volumes

We can check out the status with.

df –h

We can unmounts the volume with:

sudo umount /volumes

We can describe the volumes with the command:

nova-describe-volumes

We can delete a volume by mentioning the volume with nova-delete-volume:

nova-delete-volume vol-00000001

It has to be noted that one volume can be attached to only one instance at most. It cannot be attached to more than one instance. However they are persistent and the changes made by one instance will be shown up in other instance when the volume is attached to it.

Terminating Instances

Instances can be ended with the euca-terminate-instances command.

euca-terminate-instances i-00000001

This terminates the instance.


Configuring and Managing instances for specific application

Once we have our instance running and we are able to login via SSH, we can deploy our applications and use it as any other server.

We can use sudo tasksel –section server to automate tasks and configure server but here we shall be doing tasks manually.

Case 1: Setting up a LAMP server instance

LAMP is short for Linux, Apache, MySQL, PHP. This tutorial shows how you can install an Apache2 webserver on an Ubuntu 11.04 server with PHP5 support (mod_php) and MySQL support. In this tutorial we use the the IP address 192.168.1.128, the IP address attached to our instance.

First we install MySQL 5 like this:

apt-get install mysql-server mysql-client

We will be asked to provide a password for the MySQL root user - this password is valid for the user root@localhost, so we don't have to specify a MySQL root password manually later on.


We install the Apache Web Server. Apache 2 is available as an Ubuntu package, therefore we can install it like this:

apt-get install apache2


Directing the browser to http://192.168.1.128, anywhere in the network and we will see the Apache2 placeholder page (It works!).


Apache's default document root is /var/www on Ubuntu, and the configuration file is /etc/apache2/apache2.conf. Additional configurations are stored in subdirectories of the /etc/apache2 directory such as /etc/apache2/mods-enabled (for Apache modules), /etc/apache2/sites-enabled (for virtual hosts), and /etc/apache2/conf.d.


We can install PHP5 and the Apache PHP5 module as follows:


apt-get install php5 libapache2-mod-php5

We must restart Apache afterwards:

/etc/init.d/apache2 restart


The document root of the default web site is /var/www. We will now create a small PHP file (info.php) in that directory and call it in a browser. The file will display lots of useful details about our PHP installation, such as the installed PHP version.


vi /var/www/info.php

We edit and write:


<?php

phpinfo();

?>


Now we call that file in a browser (e.g. http://192.168.1.128/info.php) and we see, PHP5 is working, and it's working through the Apache 2.0 Handler, as shown in the Server API line. If we scroll further down, we will see all modules that are already enabled in PHP5. MySQL is not listed there which means we don't have MySQL support in PHP5 yet.


To get MySQL support in PHP, we can install the php5-mysql package. It's a good idea to install some other PHP5 modules as well as we might need them for our applications. We can search for available PHP5 modules like this:

apt-cache search php5


We pick the ones you need and install them like this:

apt-get install php5-mysql php5-curl php5-gd php5-idn php-pear php5-imagick php5-imap php5-mcrypt php5-memcache php5-ming php5-ps php5-pspell php5-recode php5-snmp php5-sqlite php5-tidy php5-xmlrpc php5-xsl


We now restart Apache2:


/etc/init.d/apache2 restart


Finally, phpMyAdmin is a web interface through which we can manage our MySQL databases. It's a good idea to install it.

apt-get install phpmyadmin

Afterwards, we can access phpMyAdmin under http://192.168.1.128/phpmyadmin/.


Case 2: Setting up an FTP server instance

For this purpose we create another instance i-00000002 and associate another IP address – 192.168.1.129 to it. Once we SSH into it, we can install the VSFTPd (Very Secure FTP daemon) in order to set an FTP server.

sudo apt-get install vfstpd

Before deploying it, we modify the VSFTPd for deployment. We edit the /etc/vsftpd.conf and set it accordingly to our needs.

sudo vim /etc/vsftpd.conf

We make the following changes

We don’t want anonymous login:

anonymous_enable=NO

Enable local users:

local_enable=YES

The ftpuser should be able to write data:

write_enable=YES

Port 20 need to turned off, makes vsftpd run less privileged:


connect_from_port_20=NO

Chroot everyone:

chroot_local_user=YES

We set umask to 022 to make sure that all the files (644) and folders (755) you upload get the proper permissions.

local_umask=022

Finally after all configuration is done, we restart our vftpd and our FTP server is ready for deployment.

sudo service vsftpd restart

Case 3: Setting up a Team Fortress 2 Game Server Instance

For this purpose we create another instance i-00000003 and associate another IP address – 192.168.1.130 to it. Once we SSH into it we configure to run our Source Server on port 27015.


One extra step that we might want to do is to create an account for running the srcds process. This isn’t at all required, but it is good practice. The standard practice seems to be creating and account called “hlds” and using that account to run the process.


We also have to either allocated a publically routable IP or we have port forward port 27015 from the WAP IP to the Local Public IP assigned (192.168.1.130) to the host.


The installation of the Source Dedicated Server, srcds is handled entirely by the hldsupdatetool created by Valve. This simple little tool will handle the download and installation of your base Source Dedicated Server. The first step in this process is to get the hldsupdatetool.


wget http://www.steampowered.com/download/hldsupdatetool.bin


This will download hldsupdatetool.bin to our current directory. Next we need to give this file execute permissions and the run it.


chmod +x hldsupdatetool.bin

./hldsupdatetool.bin


This will run the tool. It will present us with a license agreement, type “yes” and we hit enter to proceed. It will install steam into the current directory.


Now we have to run the steam client, which will check to see if it is currently up to date and download a whole bunch of updates. This will take some time.


./steam


Now that steam is up to date and ready to run we are ready to install the Team Fortress 2 server. We do this via the steam client by giving it the following command.


./steam -command update -game tf -dir .


The dot after the -dir flag tells it to install the game server based in the current directory. We can tell it to install wherever we want, but using home directory here.


Once it has finished downloading everything it will return to the console. The game server has been completely installed.


Now that our Team Fortress 2 server is installed, configured and ready to go it’s time to start it up. We can do so by running the following command.


./srcds_run -game tf +map ctf_2fort


However, we probably want to be able to log out of your SSH session from time to time. So you will need to run srcds as a service. To do this we will use a shell script and the Screen utility. Screen is a command line multitasking tool that will allow you execute the process and detach it from your current session. We start by installing screen.


sudo apt-get install screen


Now we’re going to create a script called “srcds” in the /etc/init.d folder that will let you start, restart and stop the server with a very simple command.


wget ftp://fosspowered.com/common/srcds

sudo cp srcd /etc/init.d


It’s a script from FreeNerd.net which works well.

We can now control the server via the following commands:


/etc/init.d/srcds start

/etc/init.d/srcds restart

/etc/init.d/srcds stop

This the configuration for the TF2 dedicated Server is complete.

There is no end to the types of use we can put to our instance as each instance is an indepenedent machine and could be used for a variety of purposes from Web, to development, to gaming purposes. Other uses can be as an NFS Server, as a SAMBA Server, Proxy Server, etc.

As a result of installing Ubuntu and configuring OpenStack, and then setting up the instances, we are able to roll out Virtual Private Servers for a variety of applications and maximizing our physical hardware.

Limitations of Project

Since the project is a single node cloud infrastructure build on commodity hardware and powered by regular internet access, there are various limitations.

  • Since there is only one node, the number of instances to run with reasonable performance will be limited (upto 5).

  • High Computational Workload cannot be handled.

  • Bandwidth for the infrastructure is not suitable for handling many requests.

  • Since we provide LAN IP as “public IP” for the instances, the amount of services provided by the cloud infrastructure is limited.

Application Area and Future Perspective

The cloud infrastructure can be applied to make best use of the existing hardware for an organization. With the OpenStack cloud implementation, Virtual Appliances can be created and deployed with ease and making the most efficient usage of the computing resources while at the lowest cost.

For IT administrators it offers easier administration and management, while for end users it offers an easy provisioning of VM images.

In this project we can attach more physical machines which would form a unified base with respect to which we can manage our infrastructure without bothering about low level details. It can also provide fault-tolerance since if one physical machine fails and all its instances die, then another machine will provide redundancy and re-launch the instance suffering minimal downtime.

We can also use it as a base for Apache Hadoop framework which enables applications to work with thousands of computational independent computers and petabytes of data. Hadoop was derived from Google's MapReduce and Google File System (GFS) papers.

These among many are applications and future possibilities with this project.

Appendix A - Logging in as root User


A lot of commands in this project require the user to login as root. For root access we use the following command:

sudo su

And then enter the root password, in order to get the root prompt. It is immediately recognizable as the prompt changes from ‘$’ to ‘#’.

We can simply prefix sudo to any command to run it as root but with this we won’t need to prefix sudo.



Appendix B – Alternatives to OpenStack

Eucalyptus

Eucalyptus is a software platform for the implementation of private cloud computing on computer clusters. There is an open-core enterprise edition and an open-source edition. Currently, it exports a user-facing interface that is compatible with the Amazon EC2 and S3 services but the platform is modularized so that it can support a set of different interfaces simultaneously. The development of Eucalyptus software is sponsored by Eucalyptus Systems, a venture-backed start-up. Eucalyptus works with most currently available Linux distributions including Ubuntu, Red Hat Enterprise Linux (RHEL), CentOS, SUSE Linux Enterprise Server (SLES), openSUSE, Debian and Fedora. It can also host Microsoft Windows images. Similarly Eucalyptus can use a variety of virtualization technologies including VMware, Xen and KVM hypervisors to implement the cloud abstractions it supports. Eucalyptus is an acronym for “Elastic Utility Computing Architecture for Linking Your Programs To Useful Systems”.

Eucalyptus was the default supported cloud platform for Ubuntu till Ubuntu 10.10. It was replaced by OpenStack in Ubuntu 11.04.


CloudStack

CloudStack is open source software written in java that is designed to deploy and manage large networks of virtual machines, as a highly available, scalable cloud computing platform. CloudStack current supports the most popular hypervisors VMware, Oracle VM, KVM, XenServer and Xen Cloud Platform. CloudStack offers three ways to manage cloud computing environments: a easy-to-use web interface, command line and a full-featured RESTful API.


Windows Azure

Windows Azure is an operating system that serves as the development, service hosting, and service management environment for the Windows Azure platform. The Windows Azure platform consists of an infrastructure of hardware, software, network, and storage resources. Windows Azure handles load balancing and resource management and automatically manages the life cycle of a hosted service based on defined requirements. Developers can build and deploy applications as a hosted service for Windows Azure by using the .NET Framework, unmanaged code, or other approaches.


Appendix C – Glossary

Amazon EC2

Amazon’s Elastic Compute Cloud Web service, which provides resizable computing capacity in the cloud so developers can enjoy great scalability for building applications.


Amazon S3

Amazon Simple Storage Services — Amazon’s cloud storage service.


Cloud

A metaphor for a global network, first used in reference to the telephone network and now commonly used to represent the Internet.


Cloud operating system

A computer operating system that is specially designed to run in a provider’s datacenter and be delivered to the user over the Internet or another network. Windows Azure is an example of a cloud operating system or “cloud layer” that runs on Windows Server 2008. The term is also sometimes used to refer to cloud-based client operating systems such as Google’s Chrome OS.


Cloud Oriented Architecture

A term coined by Jeff Barr at Amazon Web Services to describe an architecture where applications act as services in the cloud and serve other applications in the cloud environment.


Cloud portability

The ability to move applications and data from one cloud provider to another. See also Vendor lock-in.


Cloud provider

A company that provides cloud-based platform, infrastructure, application, or storage services to other organizations and/or individuals, usually for a fee.


Cloud storage

A service that allows customers to save data by transferring it over the Internet or another network to an offsite storage system maintained by a third party.


Cloudsourcing

Replacing traditional IT services with cloud services.


Cloudware

Software that enables creating, deploying, running, or managing applications in the cloud.


Elastic computing

The ability to dynamically provision and de-provision processing, memory, and storage resources to meet demands of peak usage without worrying about capacity planning and engineering for peak usage.


External cloud

Public or private cloud services that are provided by a third party outside the organization.


Google App Engine

A service that enables developers to create and run Web applications on Google’s infrastructure and share their applications via a pay-as-you-go, consumption-based plan with no setup costs or recurring fees.


Google Apps

Google’s SaaS offering that includes an office productivity suite, email, and document sharing, as well as Gmail, Google Talk for instant messaging, Google Calendar and Google Docs, spreadsheets, and presentations.




Hosted application

An Internet-based or Web-based application software program that runs on a remote server and can be accessed via an Internet-connected PC or thin client. See also SaaS.


Hybrid cloud

A networking environment that includes multiple integrated internal and/or external providers.


IaaS

Infrastructure as a service — Cloud infrastructure services, whereby a virtualized environment is delivered as a service over the Internet by the provider. The infrastructure can include servers, network equipment, and software.


Internal cloud


A type of private cloud whose services are provided by an IT department to those in its own organization.


Microsoft Azure

Microsoft cloud services that provide the platform as a service (see PaaS), allowing developers to create cloud applications and services.


Middleware

Software that sits between applications and operating systems, consisting of a set of services that enable interoperability in support of distributed architectures by passing data between applications. So, for example, the data in one database can be accessed through another database.


PaaS

Platform as a service — Cloud platform services, whereby the computing platform (operating system and associated services) is delivered as a service over the Internet by the provider.


Pay as you go

A cost model for cloud services that encompasses both subscription-based and consumption-based models, in contrast to traditional IT cost model that requires up-front capital expenditures for hardware and software.


Private cloud

Services offered over the Internet or over a private internal network to only select users, not available to the general public.


Public cloud

Services offered over the public Internet and available to anyone who wants to purchase the service.


SaaS

Software as a service — Cloud application services, whereby applications are delivered over the Internet by the provider, so that the applications don’t have to be purchased, installed, and run on the customer’s computers. SaaS providers were previously referred to as ASP (application service providers).


Vendor lock-in

Dependency on the particular cloud vendor and difficulty moving from one cloud vendor to another due to lack of standardized protocols, APIs, data structures (schema), and service models.


Vertical cloud

A cloud computing environment that is optimized for use in a particular industry, such as health care or financial services.


Virtual private data center

Resources grouped according to specific business objectives.

6
